<subSubSection pageId="85" pageNumber="84" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="85.[192,1440,1187,1307]" pageId="85" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,1187,1211]" pageId="85" pageNumber="84">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is recognized by the all- black dorsum, large size, short prosternum, and small dorsal punctures that are quite reduced in size in comparison with other species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gordon and Hanley" authorityYear="2017" box="[1179,1366,1219,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Prodilis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="85" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brandi">
<emphasis box="[1179,1366,1219,1243]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="84">Prodilis brandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not a typical member of this group of species in spite of having a similar genitalia 
<typeStatus box="[1140,1196,1252,1276]" pageId="85" pageNumber="84">type</typeStatus>
. It differs by having a comparatively short prosternum and lacking epipleural depressions for femoral reception.
</paragraph>
